\begin{document}
\title{\bf Hill-Shi-Wang-Xu} \author{Notes by Roger Murray}
\date{\today}

\maketitle

$\BP^{((C_4))}\langle 1 \rangle$.

According to the slice theorem, the slices for
$\BP^{((C_4))}\langle 1 \rangle$ are given by
\begin{align*}
  &\HH\underline{\bZ}\wedge S^{n\rho} &
                                        \text{                                         corresponding
                                        to
                                        }
                                        r_1^n\gamma
                                        r_1^n
  \\
  \text{and }\phantom{...}
  &\HH\underline{\bZ}\wedge\left(C_4\phantom{}_+\wedge_{C_2} S^{(m+n)\rho_2}\right)
                                      &\text{corresponding to }(r_1^m\gamma r_1^n,\gamma r_1^mr_1^n)
\end{align*}
where $\rho$ denotes the regular representation for $C_4$ and $\rho_2$
denotes the regular representation for $C_2$. Define classes
$\mathfrak{d}_1:=N_{C_2}^{C_4}(\overline{r}_1)$ and
$s_1^i:=tr(\overline{r}_1^i)$ in
$\pi^{C_4}_\star \BP^{((C_4))}\langle 1 \rangle$. Observe that
$res(\mathfrak{d}_1^i)=r_1^i\gamma r_1^i$ and
$res(s_1^i)=\overline{r}_1^i+\gamma\overline{r}_1^i$. In particular
$s_1^i\neq (s_1)^i$. We may label our slices by
$\mathfrak{d}_1^i s_1^j$.


There are a few main strategies for computing differentials in the
$C_4$-SSS for $\BP^{((C_4))}\langle 1 \rangle$:
\begin{itemize}
\item The Slice Differentials Theorem of HHR. (Note that this is
  proven by passing to the geometric fixed points, comparing geometric
  fixed points of $ \MUR$ and $\HH\underline{\bZ}$ to say that a class
  has to die and then making a
  degree argument.)
\item Leverage the fact that the SSS is a SS of Mackey functors. For
  example in particular if the restriction of class dies on the
  $E_r$-page in the the $C_2$-SSS, then it must die on or before the
  $E_r$-page of the $C_4$-SSS.
\item Using the Leibniz rule on known differentials for products of
  things.
\item 
\end{itemize}

